{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1031"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1031"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.03,0.04,0.66,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91197"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1012"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44336"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of flu-like illness, generalised malaise, and intermittent low-grade fevers. She has a medical history of aortic valve replacement with a mechanical valve five months ago. Two months ago, she received dental fillings for several cavities. Her regular medications include warfarin and bisoprolol. On examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Poor dentition is observed. Examination of her hands reveals nails as below (Image 1).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcus aureus","Haemophilus parainfluenzae","Cardiobacterium hominis","Viridans streptococci","Enterococcus faecalis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has infective endocarditis (IE). Patients with IE typically present with fever, systemic malaise, dyspnoea, and myalgia. Risk factors for IE include any cause of transient bacteraemia, such as intravenous drug use, open skin wounds, and dental procedures. Heart surgery, including valve replacement, predisposes patients to IE. The splinter haemorrhages observed in this patient are a classic sign of IE, occurring in 15-33% of cases. These are longitudinal, reddish-brown haemorrhages under the nail. Other signs may include Osler nodes, Janeway lesions, and Roth spots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common causative organisms of IE are Gram-positive bacteria, including streptococci, staphylococci, and enterococci. In this case, \u003Cstrong\u003EViridans streptococci\u003C/strong\u003E are the most likely causative organisms due to the patient\u0027s recent dental procedure and poor dentition. \u003Cem\u003EViridans streptococci\u003C/em\u003E are common commensal bacteria of the oral cavity and are strongly associated with IE following dental procedures. Patients who have undergone dental procedures within the last three months have over three times the odds of developing IE due to \u003Cem\u003EViridans streptococci\u003C/em\u003E than other causative organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of IE overall, particularly in intravenous drug users and patients with healthcare-associated infections. However, it is less likely in this scenario given the dental history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilus parainfluenzae\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECardiobacterium hominis\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the HACEK group of organisms (Haemophilus, Aggregatibacter, Cardiobacterium, Eikenella, and Kingella). These organisms are rare causes of IE, typically affecting younger patients or those with prosthetic heart valves. While this patient has a prosthetic valve, the dental history makes \u003Cem\u003EViridans streptococci\u003C/em\u003E more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterococcus faecalis\u003C/strong\u003E is a less common cause of IE and is often associated with genitourinary or gastrointestinal procedures rather than dental work.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infective endocarditis caused by Viridans streptococci typically presents subacutely and is associated with dental procedures or poor dentition.","Splinter haemorrhages occur in 15-33% of patients with infective endocarditis and appear as longitudinal reddish-brown lines under the nails.","Patients with prosthetic heart valves are at increased risk of infective endocarditis, particularly in the first year after surgery."],"references":["Barnett R. Infective endocarditis. Lancet. 2016 Sep 17;388(10050):1148. Available from: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(24)01098-5/abstract","Duval X, Millot S, Chirouze C, et al.; EI-dents Association pour l\u0027Etude et la Pr\u00e9vention de l\u0027Endocardite Infectieuse (AEPEI) Study Group. Oral Streptococcal Endocarditis, Oral Hygiene Habits, and Recent Dental Procedures: A Case-Control Study. Clin Infect Dis. 2017 Jun 15;64(12):1678-1685. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28369398/","Manley A. Splinter haemorrhage [Internet]. DermNet. 2019. https://dermnetnz.org/topics/splinter-haemorrhage"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91197"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1031"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20181"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20181"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0ea7f40e-e907-4523-8659-1ceafe50d22d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0ea7f40e-e907-4523-8659-1ceafe50d22d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":487}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91197"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T17:30:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T17:34:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1031"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108834"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api